IV. INTERACTION WITH OTHER CLOCKS
=====================================================================
VS. THE DRAGON CULT (the War for Godhood): the Dragon Cult serves Alduin and wants to
  sacrifice the world to him; Valerius wants to BE the god-king and refuses to bow to a
  dragon. He will fund the party's war against the Dragon Cult — he is their most
  generous patron, as long as it serves his political ends. He cannot rule a world that
  gets eaten.
VS. THE DAGON CULT (Order vs. Entropy): the Dagon Cult wants to return the world to
  Dawn-Era chaos and unmaking; Valerius wants an Eternal Kingdom of stasis and hierarchy.
  He sees them as arsonists trying to burn down the house he intends to buy, and will
  hand the party intelligence on Dagon Cult cells. If Alfonso ever tips fully into
  "Unmaking" rather than mere corruption, Valerius will see him as a rabid dog to be put
  down — separate from, and compounding, the Crown grievance above.
VS. THE CIVIL WAR: he wants the war to drag on just long enough to weaken both sides,
  then end it decisively with his own Ascension. He undermines both Tullius (too rigid)
  and Ulfric (too chaotic), and has a specific play depending on which side the party
  ultimately favors:
  - Empire dominant: The Bureaucratic Coup — he integrates into Imperial administration,
    frames his vampire agents as "Imperial Special Forces" (the Volkihar Guard), and
    positions himself as the civilian savior after quietly undermining Tullius.
  - Stormcloaks dominant: The Bloodline Challenge — he uses his (overstated) genealogy to
    challenge Ulfric's claim directly: "Ulfric is a usurper. I am the blood of Harald. I
    am the blood of Ysgramor. I am the Ancient King returned."
  - Peace Council: The Saboteur — peace that strengthens the current leaders is bad for
    him, so he has Orion (formerly) or another asset assassinate a delegate to shatter
    any truce.

